A '''research program''' ([[United Kingdom|UK]]: '''research programme''') is a professional network of scientists conducting [[basic research]]. The term was used by [[philosophy of science|philosopher of science]] [[Imre Lakatos]] to blend and revise the [[normative]] model of science offered by [[Karl Raimund Popper|Karl Popper]]'s ''[[falsificationism]]'' and the descriptive model of science offered by [[Thomas Samuel Kuhn|Thomas Kuhn]]'s ''[[normal science]]''.<ref>Imre Lakatos, auth, John Worrall & Gregory Currie, eds, [https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Methodology_of_Scientific_Research_P.html?id=RRniFBI8Gi4C ''The Methodology of Scientific Research Programmes: Volume 1: Philosophical Papers''] (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1980)</ref> Lakatos found falsificationism impractical and often not practiced, and found normal science—where a ''paradigm of science'', mimicking an ''exemplar'', extinguishes differing perspectives—more [[monopoly|monopolistic]] than actual.
[[Imre Lakatos|Lakatos]] found that many research programmes coexisted. Each had a ''hard core'' of theories immune to revision, surrounded by a ''protective belt'' of malleable theories.<ref name=Bechtel>William Bechtel, ''Philosophy of Science: An Overview for Cognitive Science'' (Hillsdale NJ: Lawrence Erlbaum Assoc, 1988), ch 4 "Post-positivist philosophy of science", subch "Lakatosian research programmes", pp 60-63</ref> A research programme vies against others to be most ''progressive''.<ref name=Bechtel/> Extending the research programme's theories into new domains is ''theoretical progress'', and experimentally corroborating such is ''empirical progress'', always refusing falsification of the research programme's hard core.<ref name=Bechtel/> A research programme might ''degenerate''—lose progressiveness—but later return to progressiveness.<ref name=Bechtel/>
